<section xml:id="sec_pendula" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>The Simple Pendulum</title>

  <p>
	The figure below shows a simple pendulum: a small mass <m>m</m> at the end of a massless string of length <m>L</m>.  The pendulum has an initial angular displacement from equilibrium <m>\theta_i</m> and is released from rest at <m>t = 0</m>.
  </p>
			
			 <figure xml:id="fig_pendulum">
<title>Pendulum Figure</title>
    	<caption>A simple pendulum.</caption>
    		<image source="pendulum.png" width = "15%" ></image>
    </figure>
			
		<exercises>
			<title>Simple Pendulum Activities</title>
		<exercise>
		<title>Finding Acceleration</title>
		<task>
		<statement>
			<p>
				Sketch and label a Free-body diagram for the instant shown in the figure.
			</p>
		</statement>
		<solution>
			<figure xml:id="pendulumFBD">
<title>Pendulum Free-body Diagram</title>
    	<caption>A free-body diagram for a simple pendulum.</caption>
    		<image source="pendulumFBD.png" width = "15%" ></image>
    </figure>
		</solution>
		</task>
		<task>
		<statement>
			<p>
				Determine the moment of inertia for the system of the pendulum about an axis of rotation through the top of the string (marked by <m>\times</m> in the figure).
			</p>
		</statement>
		<solution>
			<p>
				You can treat the pendulum as a point mass <m>m</m> a distance <m>L</m> from the axis of rotation, so <m>I = mL^2</m>
			</p>
		</solution>
		</task>
		<task>
		<statement>
			<p>
				Determine the net torque on the pendulum about the top of the string (marked by <m>\times</m> in the figure).
			</p>
		</statement>
		<solution>
			<p>
				The tension force acts parallel to the string, so it acts a torque of zero on the pendulum.  Gravity, however, acts at an angle to the string, so the torque is: 
				<me>
					\tau = -mgL\sin\theta
				</me>
				where the negative sign indicates that the torque is clockwise.
				
			</p>
		</solution>
		</task>
		<task>
		<statement>
			<p>
				Use the Angular Law of Motion to solve for the angular acceleration
			</p>
		</statement>
		<solution>
			<p>
				<me>
					\tau_{net} = I\alpha
				</me>
				<me>
					-mgL\sin\theta = mL^2\alpha
				</me>
				<me>
					\alpha = -\frac{g}{L}\sin\theta
				</me>
				<me>
					\frac{d^2}{dt^2}\theta = -\frac{g}{L}\sin\theta
				</me>
				
			</p>
		</solution>
		</task>
		</exercise>
		

